issue.title: Orchestra Framework Integration & Temporal Intelligence Architecture
issue.body:
**Description**
Replace custom agent framework with Orchestra multi-agent orchestration and implement temporal intelligence architecture with periodic data consolidation cycles for construction project intelligence.

**ClaudeCode Implementation Notes**
* **Database changes needed**: 
  - Temporal knowledge graph tables for historical context storage
  - Memory layer models for pattern storage and project intelligence
  - Orchestra task execution history and orchestration logs
  - Project intelligence snapshots (daily/weekly consolidated data)
* **API endpoints required**: 
  - `/orchestration/daily-cycle` - Trigger daily data collection orchestration
  - `/orchestration/weekly-intelligence` - Generate weekly intelligence reports
  - `/intelligence/project-health/{project_id}` - Get project health scores
  - `/memory/patterns/{project_id}` - Access historical pattern data
  - `/agents/orchestra` - Orchestra agent management endpoints
* **Frontend components needed**: 
  - Intelligence dashboard for orchestrated insights
  - Temporal pattern visualization components
  - Orchestra task execution status displays
* **Tests to write**: 
  - Orchestra agent orchestration tests
  - Memory layer pattern recognition tests
  - Temporal intelligence cycle tests
  - WebSocket updates for orchestrated results

**Acceptance Criteria**
* Orchestra framework integrated replacing custom agent system
* Temporal knowledge graph implementation for construction data
* Daily data collection orchestration across Procore/Autodesk/Primavera agents
* Weekly intelligence synthesis with historical pattern analysis
* Memory layer for construction-specific pattern storage and retrieval
* Cost-optimized periodic processing (60-80% reduction vs real-time)
* WebSocket updates for orchestrated intelligence results
* Predictive analytics for schedule drift and budget variance
* Cross-project learning capabilities

**Tasks:**
* **Install and configure Orchestra framework**
  - Add mainframe-orchestra dependency
  - Configure Orchestra agents for construction systems
  - Replace custom agent classes with Orchestra Agent framework

* **Implement temporal intelligence architecture**
  - Create ConstructionMemoryLayer class with temporal knowledge graph
  - Build pattern recognition engine for construction-specific insights
  - Design daily/weekly orchestration cycles

* **Build Orchestra agent orchestration**
  - Create data collection conductor agent with Conduct tool
  - Implement specialized agents for Procore, Autodesk, Primavera
  - Build intelligence synthesis agent using memory layer context

* **Develop construction intelligence use cases**
  - Schedule drift detection with historical velocity patterns
  - Budget variance prediction using cost pattern analysis
  - Project health scoring with multi-factor analysis
  - Cross-project learning and recommendation engine

* **Update database models for temporal intelligence**
  - Create tables for temporal knowledge graph storage
  - Add models for construction pattern storage
  - Implement project intelligence snapshot tables

* **Integrate with existing WebSocket architecture**
  - Update WebSocket handlers for Orchestra task results
  - Stream orchestrated intelligence updates to frontend
  - Maintain real-time updates while using periodic processing

* **Add configuration for periodic orchestration**
  - Daily data collection scheduling
  - Weekly intelligence synthesis configuration
  - Memory layer retention and cleanup policies

* **Write comprehensive tests**
  - Orchestra agent coordination tests
  - Temporal intelligence accuracy tests
  - Memory layer pattern storage/retrieval tests
  - End-to-end orchestration workflow tests

**Technical Implementation Notes:**
```python
# Key Orchestra integration points
from mainframe_orchestra import Agent, Task, Conduct

# Replace current agent system
coordination_agent = Agent(
    agent_id="construction_coordinator",
    role="construction data orchestrator",
    tools=[Conduct.conduct_tool(procore_agent, autodesk_agent, primavera_agent)]
)

# Implement periodic intelligence cycles
@daily_orchestration
async def construction_intelligence_cycle():
    project_data = await Task.create_async(
        agent=coordination_agent,
        instruction="Orchestrate complete project data collection"
    )
    return await memory_layer.consolidate_intelligence(project_data)
```

**Dependencies:**
- mainframe-orchestra>=1.0.0
- Temporal knowledge graph library (Neo4j or similar)
- Pattern recognition engine
- Existing FastAPI + WebSocket infrastructure from Task #1

**Success Metrics:**
- 60-80% cost reduction in data processing compared to real-time approach
- Successful orchestration of multi-agent construction data collection
- Accurate pattern recognition and predictive insights
- Seamless integration with existing FastAPI/WebSocket architecture
- Improved construction intelligence quality through temporal context

fs: susfs: increase susfs_open_redirect UID limit to <11000

This might be strange fix as the other kernel (probably mostly on GKI kernels) work even UID limit is less than 2000

For this kernel (or probably other non-gki kernels) it needs to be set <11000 as most user apps' UID starts at 10000+ range.

[PATCH 09/17] [BACKPORT] ptrace: Move setting/clearing ptrace_message into ptrace_stop

Today ptrace_message is easy to overlook as it not a core part of
ptrace_stop.  It has been overlooked so much that there are places
that set ptrace_message and don't clear it, and places that never set
it.  So if you get an unlucky sequence of events the ptracer may be
able to read a ptrace_message that does not apply to the current
ptrace stop.

Move setting of ptrace_message into ptrace_stop so that it always gets
set before the stop, and always gets cleared after the stop.  This
prevents non-sense from being reported to userspace and makes
ptrace_message more visible in the ptrace API so that kernel
developers can see it.

Backported to 4.14 to pass SBI Yono zygisk detections.

[FIX] marketing_card: avoid false duplicates

When sending a card mailing to recipients with duplicate emails, they
are always considered duplicate emails.

This is because:

1) We use "body" to detect duplicate emails, but "body" is never updated
with the individualized card url.

We now update the "body" as in the context of a mailing, "body_html" is
just a copy of "body".

2) Mailings consider that all emails are always the same, meaning if
it's detected that a mail was already sent to an email address during
the mailing (in a previous batch) it would skip the actual duplicate
body check.

We disable that feature for card mailings.

Describe your pull request here ---- Please read the [guidelines for Bioconda recipes](https://bioconda.github.io/contributor/guidelines.html) before opening a pull request (PR). ### General instructions * If this PR adds or updates a recipe, use "Add" or "Update" appropriately as the first word in its title. * New recipes not directly relevant to the biological sciences need to be submitted to the [conda-forge channel](https://conda-forge.org/docs/) instead of Bioconda. * PRs require reviews prior to being merged. Once your PR is passing tests and ready to be merged, please issue the `@BiocondaBot please add label` command. * Please post questions [on Gitter](https://gitter.im/bioconda/Lobby) or ping `@bioconda/core` in a comment. ### Instructions for avoiding API, ABI, and CLI breakage issues Conda is able to record and lock (a.k.a. pin) dependency versions used at build time of other recipes. This way, one can avoid that expectations of a downstream recipe with regards to API, ABI, or CLI are violated by later changes in the recipe. If not already present in the meta.yaml, make sure to specify `run_exports` (see [here](https://bioconda.github.io/contributor/linting.html#missing-run-exports) for the rationale and comprehensive explanation). Add a `run_exports` section like this: ```yaml build: run_exports: - ... ``` with `...` being one of: | Case | run_exports statement | | -------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- | | semantic versioning | `{{ pin_subpackage("myrecipe", max_pin="x") }}` | | semantic versioning (0.x.x) | `{{ pin_subpackage("myrecipe", max_pin="x.x") }}` | | known breakage in minor versions | `{{ pin_subpackage("myrecipe", max_pin="x.x") }}` (in such a case, please add a note that shortly mentions your evidence for that) | | known breakage in patch versions | `{{ pin_subpackage("myrecipe", max_pin="x.x.x") }}` (in such a case, please add a note that shortly mentions your evidence for that) | | calendar versioning | `{{ pin_subpackage("myrecipe", max_pin=None) }}` | while replacing `"myrecipe"` with either `name` if a `name|lower` variable is defined in your recipe or with the lowercase name of the package in quotes. ### Bot commands for PR management
Please use the following BiocondaBot commands: Everyone has access to the following BiocondaBot commands, which can be given in a comment:
@BiocondaBot please add label Add the please review & merge label.
@BiocondaBot please fetch artifacts Post links to CI-built packages/containers.
You can use this to test packages locally.
Note that the @BiocondaBot please merge command is now depreciated. Please just squash and merge instead. Also, the bot watches for comments from non-members that include `@bioconda/` and will automatically re-post them to notify the addressed ``.

payload.description: Builder vs. Breaker is a reproducible agentic pipeline built with LangGraph and open-source LLMs. A Breaker invents failing/property-based tests, a Builder applies minimal patches with ReAct tool use, a Critic gates risky edits, and a Referee runs. It also logs Tree-of-Thoughts plans, Debate, and Reflexion memory for transparent, auditable runs.
